<font color="#FF0000">THOUGHTS ON MYTHS &amp; FACTS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jan 14  1:57:32 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
1-Apocalypse Now was a riff on Joseph Conrad's Heart Of Darkness, a novel of late 19th century tropical Africa. As such, Vietnam serves as a canvas on which to project a 1960's take on the basic story. My wife has never let me take her to a Vietnam movie again since seeing it with me when it first came out. I could almost breath the dust at the beginning of Platoon, but Oliver's Vietnam is a funhouse distortion.<br><br>
2-When I go into high schools to teach a class on the war; the first thing I usually find myself doing is dispelling the image of Vietnam Veterans as crazed druggies. It gets a little old after awhile.<br><br>
3-Ah yes, the media...Initially the media were all behind the war. Unfortunately, after being fed BS a few times, many reporters turned cynical and refused to believe anything they were told. Eventually, this sort of thing has run rampant through our whole society. How many of us after 30 years of various revelations of official misdeeds are as trusting of government as our grandparents? I get very nervous when I hear Veterans using the same &quot;stab-in-the-back&quot; language as the German army after WWI. <br><br>
4-I only have anecdotal data on suicides, but my work and volunteer activities bring me into contact with dozens of people regularly. Suicides of Vietnam Veterans are greater than for all the rest. My VVA chapter has experienced 2 very painful ones in ten years of existence, plus one drug overdose death that was a possible suicide. <br><br>
5-Would like to know the source of the 18% higher income for Vietnam Veterans. I know most are doing well. I also know that 35-40% of the homeless on the streets of Philadelphia are veterans, many of them Vietnam era. Have worked on 2 Veterans Standdowns; so they are not a figment of my imagination.<br><br>
6-ARVNs &amp; RF/PFs- Like many troops throughout history many fought very well and many didn't. The record was uneven, largely to great disparities in the competence of their commanders and training. When my VVA chapter invited an ARVN ex-POW group to our open house; we lost 6 members. As the current president, my executive board just tolerates my continued contacts with the Vietnamese community provided I don't bring any home. My sympathies are with those who spent from 2 to 16 years in re-education camps, and the rank and file who often had pay stolen and sometimes hadn't seen their wives in 5 years. <br><br>
7-The South Vietnamese National Police were often as bad as the myth. The district police chief in Bong Son could teach a few things to his contempararies in Chicago, from taking 25% off the top of an original damage claim amount (if the amount was reduced by investigation below this-tough luck to the claiment, he got his) to selling security clearances.<br><br>
8-There were honest village chiefs. I knew one. I doubt if he's alive; as somebody like him would have been more of a danger to the Communists than a crook.<br><br>
9-&quot;If we would have only done (_______); we would have won the war.&quot;? I hear variations on this incessantly. Trouble is everybody forgets basic Clausewitz; &quot;War is an extention of politics by other means.&quot; Assuming the Reds are chased into the hills on the Chinese border; Who shall fill the vacuum in North and South Vietnamese politics and form a stable, united government? Did somebody say, &quot;Occupation?&quot;. How long? 5 years, 10 years, 20? From everything I've seen and read, I believe a total military victory over North Vietnam would have resulted in 15 to 20 years of occupation. I also believe the American people would have accepted that in a pig's eye.
<p><code>-- turtle@plantaganet  (Gerald Alan Ney, The Herd, 68-69) </code><p>


